│ stop({"edit_points": [[7288, 7289, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp"]],    │
│ "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash is an assertion failure in             │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF(), which compares the VPlan-based cost model's     │
│ chosen VF against the legacy cost model's chosen VF. The assertion allows disagreement     │
│ only if the VPlan contains additional simplifications not accounted for by the legacy      │
│ model. In this reproducer, the assertion fires, meaning the VPlan-based and legacy cost    │
│ models disagree and the code does not recognize any additional simplifications.\n\n2.      │
│ Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe log shows the assertion at LoopVectorize.cpp:7360: \"VPlan cost  │
│ model and legacy cost model disagreed\". The debug-only run doesn't print more, but the    │
│ first transformation point is computeBestVF where it calculates cost using cost(VPlan, VF) │
│ and compares with selectVectorizationFactor (legacy). The path then calls                  │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications to decide whether disagreement is acceptable.\n\n3.  │
│ Root Cause Analysis:\nLooking at planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(VPlan &Plan,        │
│ ElementCount VF, VPCostContext &CostCtx, Loop *TheLoop, LoopVectorizationCostModel &CM),   │
│ the function tries to detect if VPlan has simplifications by checking instructions in the  │
│ original loop not represented in the VPlan nor skipped by CostCtx.\nThe relevant code:\n   │
│ return any_of(TheLoop->blocks(), [...](Instruction &I) {\n    if (isa<PHINode>(&I)) return │
│ false;\n    return !SeenInstrs.contains(&I) &&\n                                           │
│ !CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true) &&\n           !CM.canTruncateToMinimalBitwidth(&I, │
│ VF);\n  });\nNote skipCostComputation is called with a hardcoded 'true' instead of         │
│ reflecting the actual VF's vector/scalar nature (VF.isVector()). This mismatched parameter │
│ can lead to incorrect classification of which instructions are skipped by the VPlan-based  │
│ cost model. As a result, planContainsAdditionalSimplifications may return false even when  │
│ there are extra simplifications, or vice versa, causing the assertion to fire              │
│ unnecessarily when the two cost models disagree legitimately.\nGiven the function          │
│ signature includes VF, it's clear the intent is to use VF to decide vector context. The    │
│ hardcoded 'true' is a bug.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n- File:                           │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp\n- Lines: 7288-7289\n- Change:\n  From:\n  │
│ !CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true) &&\n  To:\n    !CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I,     │
│ VF.isVector()) &&\n\nThis uses the actual ElementCount VF to determine whether the cost    │
│ context is vector or scalar for skipping cost computation, aligning                        │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications with the intended behavior.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe   │
│ assertion failure arises because planContainsAdditionalSimplifications erroneously uses a  │
│ constant 'true' for vector context, leading to incorrect detection of extra                │
│ simplifications and thus not allowing valid disagreements between the VPlan and legacy     │
│ cost models. Replacing 'true' with VF.isVector() ensures the check accurately reflects the │
│ vectorization factor under consideration. This should prevent the spurious assertion and   │
│ allow the VPlan-based cost model to legitimately differ when extra simplifications are     │
│ present."})                                                                                │
